\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 
\par The percentage of letters indicating general morale is higher than last week, but over a longer period it is about average for a group composed mainly of officers, whose letters normally give more frequent indications of morale than do those of enlisted m
e
n. The average condition of morale indicated is excellent, as usual, 98% good. This has varied very little in the six weeks during which a check has been kept by this office. Resumption of the offensive in Tunisia is reflected in the mail and gives rise t
o many optimistic predictions, but this makes surprisingly little difference in the level of morale, which continued good during the Axis advance.
\par 
\par In this connection, it should be noted that many letters, both from officers and enlisted men, repeat a r
umor or state a belief that the writers will be sent home either on leave or permanently as soon as the Tunisian campaign is over. This causes cheerful optimism at present, but it is sure to cause complaint and a slump in morale if this prediction proves 
to be ill-founded. If an announcement on this subject were made before the rumor becomes still more widespread, it might prevent future disappointment and difficulty.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 Some typical expressions on general morale:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261\charrsid13261201 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 "My morale has gone up 100% since I've been here where it counts all the time." (Officer, 12th A.F.).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 
"I thought how lucky we are to be serving in the best fed, best equipped army in the world." (Officer, AFHQ).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 
"I also am satisfied about everything, doing my part, although small, for Democracy. As Cervantes said--'Liberty is a cause which merits even the giving of one's life." (A Spanish-American soldier writing in Spanish, 213th C.A. (A.A.)).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 
"Honey first place we don't want come back till here is over. When we come back we want stay back. We want stay with piece like we want." (Sold\-ier whose wife asked him to come home, 1O53 M.P. Co.).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 "Would like to be in Augusta today. . . But instead I am a hero or some
\-thing way over here in Africa. I'm awful sore at those Germans. I'm going to tromp le 'em and end the war quickly. S\rquote help me, I'll mow 'em down." (Officer, 751st Tank Bn.).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 
Aside from such expressions of high morale at the moment, letters rather frequently allude to permanent benefits derived by the writers from army life. Examples:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 "You remember that inferiority complex that I always had? Well I have\-
n't got it any more, as I joined the army and lost it." (51st Sig. Co. Serv. Grp..
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 
"I'm going to be able to get along with people a whole lot better when I get out of this war. We have to share.  everything to such an extent that it has cured an antisocial condition that had grown on me back in the states. . .I find it not hard to knuck
le under any more, and very few people who I can't get along with. . .Getting along with people is the magic key to most things we want." (Officer, HQ, EBS).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261\charrsid13261201 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 "This is broadening my outlook and showing me many things I could never learn by sitting at hom
e. It is also increasing my appreciation of all the things I accepted as a necessary part of life." (Officer, 185th P.A. Bn.).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 A few special comments from the Air Corps:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261\charrsid13261201 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 "I'd much rather be here than at home." (Officer, 94th Fighter Sq.). 
Apropos of commendation of his unit: "Gosh, I could hardly believe he was talking about us. We haven't done so much; I think we are just trying to make up for the fact that we don't go into combat. . .by pushing 
our missions through. . ." (Officer, 17th Troop Carrier Squadron).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid877261\charrsid13261201 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 "I know you and all my friends are praying for me for otherwise would not be as safe now as I am. . .I'll tell you just before we get near 
our target and encounter fighters and anti-aircraft fire--I look up at God and ask him to please help me through the danger ahead--then after I am on my way back home I thank him for protecting me. . ." (Officer, 3O1 Bomb Grp.).
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3702390 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 "The air corps didn't turn out so glamorous after all. Not here in 
Africa, anyway. Where the sun seldom shines, where it's cold and damp, where there's not a white girl for fifty miles, without a damn place to go or anywhere to spend your money, to live in a mud-hole in the ground, never 
taking a bath, never eating a half decent meal, to wear dirty clothes, to work from dawn to dusk to keep the airplanes flying only to have Jerry come over and bomb or strafe the hell out of you and your planes. Old General 
Sherman wasn't far from wrong when he said, 'War is Hell'." (Officer, 47}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13261201\charrsid13261201  Bomb Grp.).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13261201 
